EDA - 2016 Presidential Campaign Contributions in Pennsylvania

Introduction

This is an exploration of the political contributions during the 2016 presidential race in Pennsylvania. This should provide an interesting look into one of the closest swing states in the general election. It also happens to be my home state.

This exploratory data analysis will answer basic questions about the political contributions to campaigns in Pennsylvania. How much money was donated and to which candidates? From where in the state did the contributions come from? In what quantities and in what frequency were people most likely to donate? Which candidate and which political party got the most donations? And can we glean any insights into enthusiasm or participation levels?

Heres the data source: http://fec.gov/disclosurep/pnational.do

To begin, well look at the structure of the data.

The data is a bit messy. There are 18 variables, mostly categorical. The only quantitative variable is contribution amount. We want to know who donated, who received the donation, how much, where, and when. The important variables for this are candidate id/candidate name, contribution amount, contributor name, contributor zip code, and contribution date.

We can possibly look at some of these other variables for some additional information, but with the amount of information, success seems doubtful. For example, consider contributor occupation. Perhaps theres some insight into what these donors do, but at 8496 different values in the data, things dont look too optimistic without some major categorizational effort.

Theres one major variable missing: party affiliation. This should be easy to deduce with some data wrangling. Well create a map of candidates to their party and add it to the data.

There are ~240K contributions total. Out of a state of ~13M, that doesnt seem like a lot. Is that an indicator of low enthusiasm levels in general?

Heres a birds eye view of the data. Ill give some first impressions before getting to the plots.

First, the candidate ids match the candiate names exactly. This is good. It makes graphing this categorical variable easy. As for the data, Hillary Clinton got the most contributions by far, followed by Bernie Sanders. These two Democrats combined got ~6x as many contributions as the next candidate, Donald Trump, the Republican nominee. Thats a bit surprising given the outcome of the vote in the state. Maybe not as Pennsylvania has gone Democrat since 1988 and was considered a part of Clintons blue wall. Finally, going off this stat, Sanders had some real ground support in the state. Oh what could have been.

Next, contributor name. Im not an expert in campaign finance laws, but it looks like people can contribute multiple times. 187 times in fact as the most prolific contributor did. It would be interesting to see if number of contributions has any correlation with party.

As for contributor city and zip, no surprise here. Philadelphia leads and Pittsburghs actually a pretty close second. The city and zip codes need cleaned up. Ill probably do that for the zip codes. Im going to venture a guess and say the cities make the most donations.

On to contributor employer and occupation, we find that one group leads the pack: retirees. That makes a lot of sense. Older people are more politically active. Also, whats going on with so many unemployed people donating? Students? This data needs some cleaning, but hopefully we can gain some insights.

For the contribution date, Id say there are probably two important periods in an election: the primaries and the general. Elections also contain critical moments, or crisis points. Perhaps a plot of contribution frequency by date could reveal peaks and valleys of contributions. Do supporters contribute more or less after a scandal or controversy? A look into when and how frequently people donated may give insights into levels of enthusiasm.

And finally to the contribution amount, nothing too surprising. It looks like theres a few weird outliers, like a $93K refund and a $10k donation. Not sure whats going on there. It looks like the vast majority of contributions were under $100. An analysis of contribution amount by candidate and party should yield interesting insights.

The rest of the variables contain minutiae thats too technical for this cursory analysis. So well ignore them.

Now onwards to the plots.

For contributes by zip code, first well quickly cleanup the zip codes to be in the 5 digit format.

Contributions came from 1639 different zip codes in PA. There are 2174 total zip codes in the state. So ~500 zip codes did not contribute at all. Looking at the summary data, most zip codes did not have many contributions. Makes sense, I suppose. PA has some really rural areas.

The plot of the contribution by zip code reveals a very positively skewed histogram. Most contributions are concentrated in certain zip codes.

Heres a peak into the top donating zip codes. And sure enough, all the top 10 are either in Pittsburgh or Philadelphia, Pennsylvanias two largest cities. In the top 25 there are some others, like 16801, which is Penn State and 17601, which is Lancaster, PA, a smaller city Im not too familiar with. A few surburbs also make the list. It would be interesting to categorize zip codes into urban and rural, or some similiar categorization and analyse that. At 2k+ zip codes however, that may be beyond the scope of this project.

Now well turn our attention to the contributor occupation and employer data. Again, Ill do some data aggregation to get a count of each type.

Listing the top occupations, we see that that RETIRED leads the list, followed by NOT EMPLOYED. Further down we see some tradtional professional jobs like attorney, professor, physician, consultant, manager, teacher, etc. There are also a few different occupations that all fall under the umbrella of software. I wonder who they donated to.

Moving on to look at contributions by date. Per usual, some data manipulation is needed. Well format the dates to make sorting and comparision easier.

Here were some important dates for the 2016 presidential election:

May 16 - PA Primaries July 18 - Republican Convention July 25 - Democratic Convention September 26 - First Debate October 9 - Second Debate October 19 - Third Debate November 7 - General Election

These are the official dates for important events. Other things obviously happened during the campaign. Maybe the data will point those out without us going out of our way to find them.

As for the data itself, the earliest contribution date is July 2014. That seems very early for the 2016 presidential race. These campaigns seem way too long. The median contribution date is June 2016, which makes sense as its right after the primaries and just before the convention.

Univariate Analysis

To summarize the above findings, most people contributed small amounts of money. Democrats overwhelmingly lead in political contributions received. And contributions followed a relatively predictable path in frequency based on the general milestones of an election.

I created one new variable: party. I also transformed the date variable into a YYYY-MM-DD format.

Bivariate Plots

Now well turn our attention to analysing relationships between the variables in our data. Well look at things like contribution amount and contribution frequency per candidate, per party, per zip code, and per occupation. Hopefully some interesting insights emerge in exploring these relationships.

Our first plot in this section will show the contributions raised by party. The Democrats raised $15,000,000 and the Republicans raised $10,000,000. This gap is a bit closer than the # of contributions graphed above, so it seems Republicans make bigger donations.

Next well look at a boxplot of individual contributions. Well limit the contributions to between 0 and 2700, which is the upper limit for individuals per the rules. To make it readable, well add a log10 scale for the y axis.

Nothing too surprising here. Republicans have higher donations in general. The third party candidates have the highest of the three.

For amount raised by candidates, well do some data aggregation first. And then plot the results.

The first plot will be the usual jumbled mess of 24 candidates, just to get a sense of things overall. The sorted table of total contribution amounts will shed light on which bars belong to which.

Clinton received the most money in contributions by far. She raised 3x as the next candidate, Trump. Sander did pretty well considering he only lasted till the primaries.

Next, well look at the boxplots of the contributions amounts made to the top candidates. There will be three groups: general election candidates, primary candidate Democrats, and some primary candidate Republicans.

There are a few interesting takeaways from these boxplots. Keep in mind the y axis is log10 scaled.

For a populist candidate, Trump had less spread and higher mean contribution amounts than Clinton. Hes still a Republican it seems.

For the Democrats, Sanders had smaller contributions with a lot more variation. Lessig and OMalley had more per contribution than some of the top Republicans. I dont think they had much support, so maybe those that did probably tended to be more enthusiastic.

For the Republicans, Jeb had the support of those who make higher contributions. His mean contribution amount was ~$900. Compare that to Sanders mean contribution amount: $27. Carson and Cruz had really similar amounts per contribution, which suggests that they share a base.

Bivariate Analysis

In sum, Democrats raised more money than Republicans. Republicans in general had a higher mean $ amount per contribution. Ted Cruz and Ben Carson, two Republican nominees, had very similar spreads in terms of $ per contribution. This suggests they may have similar supporters, and thus share a base of support. One stark comparison was the mean and median $ amount per contribution between Democrat Bernie Sanders and Republican Jeb Bush. Jeb obviously had much bigger contributions from far fewer people.

Multivariate Plots

Next, well switch to looking at contribution data per occupation. Above we saw that retirees, unemployed, and various professional careers made the most frequent contributions. Here well hopefully see how much and to who they donated.

To accomplish this, well first do some data wrangling to get two dataframes: contribution total amount by occupation and party, and contribution total amount by occupation and candidate.

Theres almost an endless amount of analysis we could do here. First, well look at which occupations donated the most and for which party.

These are interesting. Retired folks donating to both parties lead the list. The unemployed donate a lot of money to Democrats. Attorneys, physicians, lawyers, consultants, and professors donating to Dems round out the top of the list. Not until you get down to the last 10 spots do you groups donating to Republicans: upper level management. Lastly, whats up with Homemakers donating so much money to candidates? Seems like a good way to double up on donations.

Next, well focus on the top two groups: the retired and the unemployed.

Im actually a bit surprised by the numbers for the contribution amounts for retired folk. By party, things are pretty much even. Clinton did much better than Trump, raising 2x as much, though. However, the Republican field had many more candidates, which diluted contributions. Its interesting how much less money Sanders received from this group as well.

Sanders crushed in contributions received from the unemployed. These may also be students (but maybe not as students have their own category).

Heres a plot of the top professions with contributions amounts by party. Dems really rake in the contributions from these professional careers. It would be interesting to see if this is a national trend or something unique to Pennsylvania. I also added students because why not.

Next, lets take a look at donation frequency by date for the parties and candidates.

Wow. Republican donations really took a dive after the convention, whereas the Democrats kept going strong all the way to election night.

The same trend occurs when we limit things to just Clinton and Trump. Trumps contributions really took a dip after the convention, whereas Clintons kept going strong all the way to the election.

Whats really striking is Trump barely has any activity until the Republican convention. Clinton has donations flowing in even during the primary.

Multivariate Analysis

In sum, several things stood out. Retirees make the most donations to both parties as a group. And they donate equally to each party. The unemployed also donate a significant chunk of money, and mostly all of it goes to Democrats. Democrats get a lot more money from those in traditional professional careers, while Republicans get more money from business related professions. A frequency polygon of the number of contributions over time gives a good glimpse into enthusiasm. Democrats had the edge in that for the most part as well.

Final Plots

Plot 1 - Contribution frequency over the span of the election

I chose this plot because it seems like the best example of measuring enthusiasm. In my opinion, contribution frequency is a better measure of enthusiasm than contribution amount. This plot suggests that Clinton had an overwhelming amount of enthusiasm as she had the most contributions at basically every point. And these contributions seemed to keep flowing until the election. Trumps contributions peaked right around the conventions and then plumetted. He really did not have much going for him in terms of donations. Its astonishing that he narrowly pulled out a victory in the state.

Plot 2 - Donations per party by occupation

I found the donations by occupation really interesting. We trust these professionals to perform vital functions in our society, so its intersting to see who they support politically. It seems that the Democrats received a lot more money from these groups than Republicans.

As for retirees, its interesting to see just how much more money they contribute. Granted, there probably are a bunch more retirees than actively practicing attorneys or lawyers, and were not really sure which professions these retirees had in their working years. However, it is still interesting how much they give. Whats also striking is that they seem to donate an equal amount of money to Democrats and Republicans alike. This does suggest that retirees are more politically active than other sections of the population.

Plot 3 - Contribution frequency by date between start of election cycle and Democratic primary for Bernie Sanders and Hillary Clinton

This is good stuff. If we accept this idea of contribution frequency as a measure of enthusiasm, then Pennsylvania definitely felt the Bern until about the PA primary. Sanders contribution frequency handily leads Clinton until right around the PA primary. With that said, Clinton won the primary 56% - 44% (see https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pennsylvania_Democratic_primary,_2016). Thats a solid win for her. About 1.6M people voted in the Democratic primary, and 2/3 of the ~240k donations went to Democrats. So maybe Benie only had the support of a dedicated minority. That raises an interesting question though. Who contributes to political campaigns and who actually votes?

Reflection

This data has only one quantative variable and a bunch of qualitative variables. So naturally most insights involve the amount of $ contributed to either candidates or parties by certain groups. The frequency of contributions from donors also produced a number of insights.

I made several decisions in working with the data. For most of the plots, I omitted negative contribution amounts, i.e.refunds. In some of the plots, I omitted donations outside the allowed individual of $2700. In some I didnt.

I did a fair amount of data wrangling throughout the investigation. The dplyr package came in handy time and time again in aggregating data, e.g.aggregating contribution amounts by party and occupation. All of my plots used the ggplot2 package, as Im most familiar with using it. These packages are fast and easy to use, so no difficulties in utilizing them. I also added one variable to the main data set: party. This made aggregating data by party easier. I also transformed the dates into a sortable format, i.e. (YYYY-MM-DD), which made things easier.

As for difficulties, I did not face many. Luckily this data set only had ~250k rows, which made it very manageable. I did run into some performance issues initially in plotting things. Some of the early plotting attempts took forever to produce, until I started aggregating data and plotting that. This decoupled the plotting function with aggregating the data, speeding things up considerably. I learned that transforming data before plotting it is a smart way to do EDA.

I unfortunately did not get to analysing contributions from specific locations in the state. It must be possible to produce some sort of map, maybe a heatmap, of contributions by zip code. This would be a great visual of enthusiasm for either parties or candidates in various regions of the state. If I were to further this investigation, I would certainly add this.

I also did not do any sort of predictive modeling. Once I have more experience, I would definitely like to revisit this data and apply some models. It would be interesting to predict things like candidate choice based on contribution amount, zip code, or occupation.
